@node What is Ollama
@section What is Ollama
@cindex Ollama, overview

Ollama is a lightweight server that runs large language models (LLMs) locally
on your computer.  Codebud does not call any external API; instead it sends
every prompt to Ollama over a plain HTTP connection on
@code{localhost:11434}.  Your code and your prompts never leave your machine.

Ollama stores model weights in a central directory, serves them through a
small REST API, and handles loading/unloading models from RAM automatically.
You install it once, pull whichever models you want, and point Codebud at
them with a single environment variable.


@node Model Hardware Requirements
@section Hardware Requirements
@cindex system requirements, models
@cindex RAM requirements

The minimum resources depend on the model you choose.  The table below lists
the practical requirements for the models Codebud recommends.

@multitable @columnfractions .35 .15 .20 .30
@headitem Model name @tab Disk @tab RAM needed @tab Gen. speed (i7-8550U)
@item @code{qwen2.5-coder:1.5b} @tab ~1 GB @tab ~2 GB @tab ~8 t/s
@item @code{qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M} @tab ~1.8 GB @tab ~4 GB @tab ~1.1 t/s
@item @code{qwen2.5-coder:7b-instruct-q4_K_M} @tab ~4.7 GB @tab ~8 GB @tab <1 t/s
@item @code{qwen2.5-coder:14b-instruct-q4_K_M} @tab ~9 GB @tab ~16 GB @tab <0.5 t/s
@end multitable

@noindent
@emph{t/s} = output tokens per second (generation phase).  Prefill (processing
the input prompt) is a separate, slower phase on CPU-only hardware: the 3B
model takes approximately 230 seconds to prefill a 360-token planning prompt
on an i7-8550U, plus ~58 seconds of generation, for a total of ~5 minutes
per agent call.  The 7B model is impractically slow on this hardware (the
same prompt exceeds 5 minutes of prefill alone).

If you have an NVIDIA GPU, Ollama uses it automatically and speeds improve
by 10--50x, making even the 7B model interactive.

@strong{Recommendation for CPU-only laptops (e.g. i7-8550U, 16 GB RAM):}
use @code{qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M}.  It fits in RAM, produces
valid JSON plans reliably, and completes a round-trip in under 6 minutes.
The 1.5B model is faster but less accurate at following structured JSON
instructions; switch to it only if 6 minutes is unacceptably slow.


@node Choosing a Model
@section Choosing a Model
@cindex choosing a model
@cindex Qwen2.5-Coder

All recommended models are from the Qwen2.5-Coder family, which is
specifically trained on source code and follows structured JSON instructions
reliably --- important for Codebud's planner.

@table @strong
@item 1.5B (smallest)
Fast enough for interactive use even on slow hardware.  May struggle with
multi-step plans or complex file edits.  Good for quick experiments.

@item 3B (recommended for CPU laptops)
The best balance of speed and capability on hardware without a dedicated GPU.
Handles Codebud's planning prompt well and usually returns valid JSON on the
first try.

@item 7B (recommended if you have a GPU or a fast desktop CPU)
Noticeably better plan quality and code generation.  Too slow for interactive
use on a 2018 laptop CPU (1--2 tokens/s means 2--5 minutes per prompt).

@item 14B and larger
Requires substantial RAM (16 GB+) and a GPU for practical use.  Not covered
in this manual.
@end table

@noindent
If you are unsure, start with @code{3b-instruct-q4_K_M}.  You can always
pull a larger model later and switch with one environment variable change
(@pxref{Selecting a Model in Codebud}).


@node Ollama Server Setup
@section Installing and Starting Ollama
@cindex installing Ollama
@cindex ollama serve

@subsection Arch Linux

@strong{Option A --- AUR (recommended):}

If you have an AUR helper, install the @code{ollama} package so that
upgrades go through pacman:

@example
yay -S ollama
# or: paru -S ollama
@end example

@strong{Option B --- official installer script:}

If you do not use the AUR, the official script works on any distribution:

@example
curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh
@end example

This installs the @command{ollama} binary to @file{/usr/local/bin/ollama} and
optionally installs a systemd service unit.  On Arch, the AUR package is
preferred because it integrates with pacman and handles the service unit
without manual steps.

@subsection Starting the server

You must have the Ollama server running before you can pull or use any model.
There are two ways to keep it running:

@table @strong
@item Foreground (for testing)
@example
ollama serve
@end example
Leave this terminal open.  Press @kbd{Ctrl-C} to stop.

@item systemd service (recommended for daily use)
@example
sudo systemctl enable --now ollama
@end example
The service starts automatically on boot.  Check its status with:
@example
systemctl status ollama
@end example
@end table

@subsection Verify the server is running

@example
curl http://localhost:11434/api/tags
@end example

You should receive a JSON response.  If you get @samp{Connection refused},
the server is not running --- start it with one of the methods above.


@node Pulling a Model
@section Pulling a Model
@cindex pulling a model
@cindex ollama pull

Download a model with:

@example
ollama pull qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M
@end example

Ollama downloads the model weights in parallel chunks and displays a progress
bar.  The download for the 3B model is approximately 1.8 GB.  It resumes
automatically if interrupted --- you can safely press @kbd{Ctrl-C} and re-run
the same command to continue.

@strong{Important:} you only need to pull a model once.  The weights are
stored permanently on disk (@pxref{Where Models Are Stored}) and reused
across Ollama restarts.


@node Listing Models
@section Listing Models
@cindex listing models
@cindex ollama list

To see every model you have downloaded:

@example
ollama list
@end example

Example output:

@example
NAME                                    ID              SIZE    MODIFIED
qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M       abc123...       1.8 GB  2 minutes ago
qwen2.5-coder:7b-instruct-q4_K_M       def456...       4.7 GB  1 hour ago
@end example

To inspect details about a specific model:

@example
ollama show qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M
@end example

You can also query the REST API directly:

@example
curl -s http://localhost:11434/api/tags | python3 -m json.tool
@end example


@node Where Models Are Stored
@section Where Models Are Stored
@cindex model storage location
@cindex ~/.ollama

Ollama stores all model data under:

@example
~/.ollama/models/
@end example

The layout inside is:

@table @file
@item blobs/
The actual weight files.  Each file is named after its SHA-256 hash,
for example @file{sha256-60e05f210007@dots{}}.  A single blob can be shared
by multiple model variants (Ollama deduplicates weights automatically).

@item manifests/
Small JSON files that map a human-readable model name such as
@samp{qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M} to the blob hashes that make up
that model.
@end table

You never need to edit these files by hand.  Use @command{ollama list},
@command{ollama pull}, and @command{ollama rm} to manage them.

@strong{Disk usage check:}

@example
du -sh ~/.ollama/models/
@end example


@node Custom Storage Location
@section Custom Storage Location
@cindex OLLAMA_MODELS
@cindex portable model storage

By default Ollama writes models to @file{~/.ollama/models/}.  You can
redirect this to any path --- a different disk partition, an external drive,
or a shared network folder --- by setting the @env{OLLAMA_MODELS} environment
variable before starting the server.

@example
export OLLAMA_MODELS=/media/external-drive/ollama-models
ollama serve
@end example

All @command{ollama pull} and @command{ollama list} operations will use that
path.  To make this permanent, add the export to your shell profile
(@file{~/.zshrc} or @file{~/.bashrc}) @emph{and} to the Ollama systemd
service override if you use one:

@example
sudo systemctl edit ollama
@end example

Then add:

@example
[Service]
Environment="OLLAMA_MODELS=/media/external-drive/ollama-models"
@end example

After saving, reload and restart the service:

@example
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl restart ollama
@end example


@node Selecting a Model in Codebud
@section Selecting a Model in Codebud
@cindex OLLAMA_MODEL
@cindex OLLAMA_BASE_URL

Codebud reads two environment variables to find the model:

@table @env
@item OLLAMA_MODEL
The exact model name to use, as it appears in @command{ollama list}.
This variable @strong{must} be set; without it Codebud falls back to
OpenAI or logs a warning and returns no plan.

@item OLLAMA_BASE_URL
The base URL of the Ollama server.  Defaults to
@code{http://localhost:11434}.  Change this only if you are running Ollama
on a different machine or a non-standard port.
@end table

Example --- run Codebud with the 3B model:

@example
export OLLAMA_MODEL=qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M
codebud run "create a hello.py that prints Hello, world"
@end example

Or inline for a one-off run:

@example
OLLAMA_MODEL=qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M codebud run "..."
@end example

Use @command{codebud models} to see all pulled models with the active one
highlighted (@pxref{The models Subcommand}).


@node Switching Models
@section Switching Models
@cindex switching models

To switch from one model to another, simply change @env{OLLAMA_MODEL} and
run Codebud again.  No restart of the Ollama server is needed; it loads and
unloads models from RAM on demand.

@example
# Switch from 3B to 7B
export OLLAMA_MODEL=qwen2.5-coder:7b-instruct-q4_K_M
codebud run "refactor agent/planner.py to add retry logic"
@end example

If the new model has not been pulled yet, pull it first
(@pxref{Pulling a Model}).


@node Transferring Models
@section Transferring Models
@cindex transferring models
@cindex copying models offline

Because model weights can be several gigabytes and bandwidth may be expensive,
you can copy already-downloaded models to another machine instead of pulling
them again.

@subsection Method 1 --- tar archive (offline copy)

On the source machine:

@example
tar -czf ollama-models.tar.gz ~/.ollama/models/
@end example

Transfer @file{ollama-models.tar.gz} by USB drive, local network, or any
other means.  On the target machine (with Ollama installed):

@example
mkdir -p ~/.ollama
tar -xzf ollama-models.tar.gz -C ~/
@end example

After extraction, @command{ollama list} on the target machine will show the
models immediately, as if they had been pulled normally.

@subsection Method 2 --- shared or portable drive (zero-copy)

If both machines can access the same physical drive or network share,
point @env{OLLAMA_MODELS} at the shared path on each machine:

@example
export OLLAMA_MODELS=/media/shared-drive/ollama-models
ollama serve
@end example

No copying is needed.  Both machines read the same blob files.

@strong{Note:} do not run two Ollama servers writing to the same
@env{OLLAMA_MODELS} path at the same time; concurrent writes can corrupt
the manifest files.


@node Removing Models
@section Removing Models
@cindex removing models
@cindex ollama rm
@cindex freeing disk space

To delete a model and reclaim disk space:

@example
ollama rm qwen2.5-coder:7b-instruct-q4_K_M
@end example

This removes the manifest and any blobs that are not shared with another
installed model.  Verify with @command{ollama list} and @command{du -sh
~/.ollama/models/}.

@strong{Warning:} this is permanent.  You will need to re-download
(@command{ollama pull}) if you want the model back.


@node Model Troubleshooting
@section Troubleshooting
@cindex troubleshooting, models

@table @strong

@item @samp{could not connect to a running Ollama instance}
The Ollama server is not running.  Start it with @command{ollama serve} or
@command{sudo systemctl start ollama}.

@item @samp{model not found}
The model name passed in @env{OLLAMA_MODEL} does not match any installed
model.  Run @command{ollama list} to see what is available, and
@command{ollama pull <name>} to download the missing model.

@item Response times are very slow (minutes per prompt)
You are likely running a model that is too large for your CPU.  Switch to a
smaller variant (@pxref{Choosing a Model}).  Also check that Ollama is not
swapping to disk:

@example
free -h
cat /proc/$(pgrep ollama)/status | grep VmRSS
@end example

If @samp{available} RAM is near zero, you need a smaller model.

@item @samp{LLM returned empty output} or request timeout in Codebud
The HTTP request timed out before Ollama finished generating.  This usually
means the model is too slow for the prompt size.  Try a smaller model, or
wait for the model to finish loading into RAM (the first request after a
server restart is always the slowest).

@item Out of memory / Ollama killed by the OOM killer
The model weights do not fit in RAM.  Check @command{ollama list} for the
model size and compare it to @command{free -h}.  Switch to a smaller model
or close other applications to free RAM.

@end table


@node Quick Recipes
@section Quick Recipes
@cindex quick recipes

The five commands you will type most often:

@table @strong

@item Start the Ollama server
@example
ollama serve
@end example

@item Download the recommended model
@example
ollama pull qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M
@end example

@item Run Codebud with that model
@example
export OLLAMA_MODEL=qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M
codebud run "your task here"
@end example

@item Back up all models to a single archive
@example
tar -czf ollama-models.tar.gz ~/.ollama/models/
@end example

@item Restore models on a new machine
@example
tar -xzf ollama-models.tar.gz -C ~/
@end example

@end table
